          <h2 style="              
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.5;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Education cuts</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Summary: The Trump administration will cut the Department of Education workforce by half, following President Trump‚Äôs proposal to eliminate the department.</strong></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The US Department of Education <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-13-03-2025-h3-3-announced-significant-layoffs" target="_blank">announced significant layoffs</a>, reducing its workforce by nearly 50%. This is in response to President Donald Trump‚Äôs proposal to eliminate the agency. Approximately 1,300 employees will be laid off, adding to the over 300 voluntarily separating from the department, and about 260 accepted a deferred resignation package.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Education Secretary Linda McMahon justified the cuts as part of efforts to improve efficiency and accountability. She acknowledged that completely shutting down the department would require Congress‚Äôs approval. The layoffs are part of broader efforts to shrink the federal government. Other agencies saw similar reductions. Critics, including unions and experts, expressed concerns over the impact on students and federal student aid.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Several offices across the country, including those in San Francisco and New York, will close, consolidating into one office in Washington, DC. Critics warned that the cuts could compromise the agency's ability to fulfill its duties effectively. They have also questioned Linda Mahon's qualifications to run the department, as her previous career was in business, not education.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
